<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="14" type="note">
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="1" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="species" species="simmonsii">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Scapania simmonsii</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms an isolated lineage within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">S.</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
subg. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" authorityYear="2012" baseAuthorityName="sect. Simmonsia (R. M. Schust.) Vana, Hentschel, Joch. Muell. &amp; Heinrichs" baseAuthorityYear="2012" class="Hepaticae" family="Scapaniaceae" genus="Scapania" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="" order="Jungermanniales" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" phylum="Bryophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="14">Scapania</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, hence, we erect a section for this species rather than using subsectional rank (
<bibRefCitation author="Schuster, RM" journalOrPublisher="Annales Botanici Fennici" pageId="1" pageNumber="14" refId="B4" refString="Schuster, RM, 1974. The Hepaticae and Anthocerotae of North America. Columbia University Press, New York." title="The Hepaticae and Anthocerotae of North America. Columbia University Press, New York." year="1974">Schuster 1974</bibRefCitation>
). Distinctive features of the monotypic section are the deflexed-involute, broad, concave ventral leaf lobes that stand away from the stem at almost right angles and leaf cell walls with very large, nodulose trigones.
</paragraph>
